abstract: Can right and left break out of their disastrous cycle?
snippet: Can right and left break out of their disastrous cycle?
lead_paragraph: Nature’s temporary solution to the crisis on the United States’ southwest border is upon us, in the form of high summer temperatures that should reduce the migration rate and relieve some of the pressure on our overcrowded camps and courts. So it’s a good time to step back and assess the disastrous cycle in which our immigration policy has been caught.

abstract: Joe Biden defended his record on race, highlighting his tenure with Barack Obama, and apologized for his remarks on working with segregationists.
snippet: Joe Biden defended his record on race, highlighting his tenure with Barack Obama, and apologized for his remarks on working with segregationists.
lead_paragraph: SUMTER, S.C. — After spending weeks under fire for his decades-long history on race and civil rights, Joseph R. Biden Jr. on Saturday gave the most forceful defense yet of his record, emphasizing his time as vice president to Barack Obama, and did something he had resisted in the past — apologize for warmly reminiscing about his working relationships with Southern segregationists.

headline_main: What It’s Like to Attend Political Rallies

abstract: The president faults his predecessor on North Korea, Iran, Turkey, NATO and the border. “I call it the ‘Obama-Biden mess,’” Mr. Trump said.
snippet: The president faults his predecessor on North Korea, Iran, Turkey, NATO and the border. “I call it the ‘Obama-Biden mess,’” Mr. Trump said.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — It took all of one minute and nine seconds for President Trump to go after his predecessor on Friday — just one minute and nine seconds to re-engage in a debate that has consumed much of his own time in office over who was the better president.

abstract: Mr. Biden reiterated that Ms. Harris had mischaracterized his position on school busing, prolonging what has been a combative period of the presidential primary.
snippet: Mr. Biden reiterated that Ms. Harris had mischaracterized his position on school busing, prolonging what has been a combative period of the presidential primary.
lead_paragraph: Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. said Friday that he had not been prepared for Senator Kamala Harris to so pointedly question his record on school busing during the first Democratic debates, extending the dispute between the two presidential candidates, who have sparred repeatedly in the week since their high-profile confrontation.

abstract: The candidates continue to address questions about school integration, prolonging the most combative period of the Democratic primary to date.
snippet: The candidates continue to address questions about school integration, prolonging the most combative period of the Democratic primary to date.
lead_paragraph: INDEPENDENCE, Iowa — Joseph R. Biden Jr. expressed frustration Thursday at Senator Kamala Harris’s pointed criticism about his 1970s-era opposition to busing, arguing that Democrats should “be talking about the future.” But he resisted the opportunity to return fire at Ms. Harris for voicing a position similar to his on school integration.
